sue is that the first time the script ran (in my earlier attempt), it got permission denied. But it seems the first batch actually worked. Let me just check if the fonts are in C:\\Windows\\Fonts now.\n\nWait, I re-read the output. So all four font files got copied and registered successfully—the D2Coding variants and their bold and ligature versions all made it through. That's actually good news. after the AddType and second foreach, ALL FOUR files got permission errors on both Copy-Item and Set-ItemProperty.\n\nOH I see - the foreach ran twice because AddFontResource triggers for each $f, but $ttfs is the same list. But the second foreach doesn't have Copy-Item... unless the whole script block is being run twice?\n\nNo wait - I see what happened. The PS1 heredoc has the entire script. The first foreach with Copy-Item ran with the new `>>` continuation prompts, and it succeeded for all 4 files. Then the AddType ran. Then the second foreach (for AddFontResource) ran. But the errors show Copy-Item, not AddFontResource.\n\nI think what happened is that the first foreach loop is repeated. The output text may have the successful messages from the first iteration, then PowerShell tried to run the loop again (maybe a parsing issue with the continuation) and got permission denied because the files were already locked. Rather than troubleshooting the admin elevation further, I could just install to the user font directory at `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Fonts` instead, which doesn't require administrator privileges.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3600,"cache_read_input_tokens":56007,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3600},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYDihf1WZJjs8wJjN2HhY","type":"assistant","uuid":"62368cc8-993c-4798-ae78-f37e3d1c1d90","timestamp":"2026-02-17T13:28:35.985Z"}
